      >
     <text xmlns="https://www.latex-project.org/ns/dflt"
        id="ID.0009"
        xmlns:Layout="http://iso.org/pdf/ssn/Layout"
        Layout:TextAlign="Justify"
        rolemaps-to="P"
       >
      <?MarkedContent page="1" ?>In the early nineties,
      <Link xmlns="http://iso.org/pdf2/ssn"
         id="ID.0010"
        >
       <?MarkedContent page="1" ?>
       <?ReferencedObject type="Annot" page="1" ?>
      </Link>
      <?MarkedContent page="1" ?>GSM was deployed in many European countries.
      <Link xmlns="http://iso.org/pdf2/ssn"
         id="ID.0011"
        >
       <?MarkedContent page="1" ?>
       <?ReferencedObject type="Annot" page="1" ?>
      </Link>
      <?MarkedContent page="1" ?>GSM of-fered for the first time international roaming for mobile subscribers. The
      <Link xmlns="http://iso.org/pdf2/ssn"
         id="ID.0012"
        >
       <?MarkedContent page="1" ?>
       <?ReferencedObject type="Annot" page="1" ?>
      </Link>
      <?MarkedContent page="1" ?>GSM’suse of Time Division Multiple Access (
      <Link xmlns="http://iso.org/pdf2/ssn"
         id="ID.0013"
        >
       <?MarkedContent page="1" ?>
       <?ReferencedObject type="Annot" page="1" ?>
      </Link>
      <?MarkedContent page="1" ?>TDMA) as its communication standardwas debated at length. And every now and then there are big discussion whetherCode Division Multiple Access (
      <Link xmlns="http://iso.org/pdf2/ssn"
         id="ID.0014"
        >
       <?MarkedContent page="1" ?>
       <?ReferencedObject type="Annot" page="1" ?>
      </Link>
      <?MarkedContent page="1" ?>CDMA) should have been chosen over
      <Link xmlns="http://iso.org/pdf2/ssn"
         id="ID.0015"
        >
       <?MarkedContent page="1" ?>
       <?ReferencedObject type="Annot" page="1" ?>
      </Link>
      <?MarkedContent page="1" ?>TDMA.
     </text>
    </text-unit>
   </Sect>
   <Sect xmlns="http://iso.org/pdf2/ssn"
