     <text xmlns="https://www.latex-project.org/ns/dflt"
        id="ID.0020"
        xmlns:Layout="http://iso.org/pdf/ssn/Layout"
        Layout:TextAlign="Justify"
        rolemaps-to="P"
       >
      <?MarkedContent page="1" ?>The reader could have forgotten all the nice acronyms, so we repeat the meaningagain.
     </text>
    </text-unit>
    <text-unit xmlns="https://www.latex-project.org/ns/dflt"
       id="ID.0021"
       rolemaps-to="Part"
      >
     <text xmlns="https://www.latex-project.org/ns/dflt"
        id="ID.0022"
        xmlns:Layout="http://iso.org/pdf/ssn/Layout"
        Layout:TextAlign="Justify"
        rolemaps-to="P"
       >
      <?MarkedContent page="1" ?>If you want to know more about Global System for Mobile communication(
      <Link xmlns="http://iso.org/pdf2/ssn"
         id="ID.0023"
        >
       <?MarkedContent page="1" ?>
       <?ReferencedObject type="Annot" page="1" ?>
      </Link>
      <?MarkedContent page="1" ?>GSM), Time Division Multiple Access (
      <Link xmlns="http://iso.org/pdf2/ssn"
         id="ID.0024"
        >
       <?MarkedContent page="1" ?>
       <?ReferencedObject type="Annot" page="1" ?>
      </Link>
      <?MarkedContent page="1" ?>TDMA), Code Division Multiple Access(
      <Link xmlns="http://iso.org/pdf2/ssn"
         id="ID.0025"
        >
       <?MarkedContent page="1" ?>
       <?ReferencedObject type="Annot" page="1" ?>
      </Link>
      <?MarkedContent page="1" ?>CDMA) and other acronyms, just read a book about mobile communication.Just to mention it: There is another Used Acronym (
      <Link xmlns="http://iso.org/pdf2/ssn"
         id="ID.0026"
        >
       <?MarkedContent page="1" ?>
       <?ReferencedObject type="Annot" page="1" ?>
      </Link>
      <?MarkedContent page="1" ?>UA), just for testingpurposes!
     </text>
